{
  "answer": "**I could not find a Ghalib couplet in the Falsafa corpus matching this description.**\n\nThe *Diwan-e-Ghalib* (mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c) contains 239 ghazals with frequent references to madness (*junoon*, *deewangi*, *vehshat*), such as in ghazal 13 (\"Baagh pa kar khafqani yeh darata hai mujhe\"), where the garden \"found in madness\" terrifies the speaker;[^1] ghazal 28 (\"Deewangi se dosh pe zunnar bhi nahin\"), on madness excusing sacred norms;[^2] ghazal 84 (\"Ishq mujh ko nahin vehshat hi sahi\"), preferring wild obsession;[^3] ghazal 96 (\"Junoon ki dastgiri kis se ho gar ho na uryaani\"), on aid for sacred madness;[^4] and ghazal 126 (\"Lo hum mareez-e-ishq ke beemaar-daar hain\"), where the speaker is a caretaker for love's \"ailing patient.\"[^5]\n\nHowever, no couplet mentions an asylum-keeper (or equivalents like madhouse warden/superintendent/darogha) asking after or seeking the speaker. Searches for key phrases (\"keeper,\" \"warden,\" \"asylum,\" \"madhouse,\" \"darogha,\" \"asking,\" \"came to ask\") across English translations returned no matches in Ghalib's work. This motif appears in Ghalib's letters and oral tradition but may not be in this Diwan edition or its translations.\n\n[^1]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 13, [p-97f459](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/13-baagh-pa-kar-khafqani-yeh-darata-hai-mujhe/translation/#p-97f459).\n[^2]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 28, [p-4ba867](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/28-deewangi-se-dosh-pe-zunnar-bhi-nahin/translation/#p-4ba867).\n[^3]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 84, [p-a4c81f](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/84-ishq-mujh-ko-nahin-vehshat-hi-sahi/translation/#p-a4c81f).\n[^4]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 96, [p-82f537](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/96-junoon-ki-dastgiri-kis-se-ho-gar-ho-na-uryaani/translation/#p-82f537).\n[^5]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 126, [p-cdb14e](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/126-lo-hum-mareez-e-ishq-ke-beemaar-daar-hain/translation/#p-cdb14e).",
